snippet.textDisplay:
I think this episode is a bit skewed towards the teen dads that actually were there for their baby, so that the episode makers could get in contact with them as a 'teen dad' rather than having to ask the girl who the father was and contact them that way.
If the episode were about teen mothers, it would be different, since teen mothers have to do something about a pregnancy and, if they keep the baby, are forced into being there for the child (whatever they might feel about doing so), but teen fathers have the ability to walk away.
I think if it were possible to have gotten in contact with a wider selection of teen dads, some of whom weren't active in accepting their role and responsibilities, this episode would have been very different.
snippet.textOriginal:
I think this episode is a bit skewed towards the teen dads that actually were there for their baby, so that the episode makers could get in contact with them as a 'teen dad' rather than having to ask the girl who the father was and contact them that way.
If the episode were about teen mothers, it would be different, since teen mothers have to do something about a pregnancy and, if they keep the baby, are forced into being there for the child (whatever they might feel about doing so), but teen fathers have the ability to walk away.
I think if it were possible to have gotten in contact with a wider selection of teen dads, some of whom weren't active in accepting their role and responsibilities, this episode would have been very different.

snippet.textDisplay:
You can tell they are teens because in every statement they only use I. "I wanted to have..." "I was going..." "I always wanted to have..." without them saying "I wanted to give a child a life..." "I wanted them to have a sibling..." "I knew I could give this child a good life, and this was the right time because..." even the planned ones, they come across as very selfish on a base level "I always wanted a child at a young age, I didn't know why, but..."

Their body language is also very nervous and defensive, feet shuffling, arms crossed, hands clasped together.

Also, "we were scared to tell anyone else." mate, if you are scared of the reactions, you probably shouldn't be planning a pregnancy, it takes emotional maturity to not care about what other people think and stand by what you have done with an honest opinion.

"If you know what you are getting yourself into by having relations..." say the man who didn't know his mother wouldn't approve of him having a child. If people are careful, they don't expect to get someone pregnant, especially when the education system is failing them so badly. No one knows how they will react in that situation. He is married and planned his pregnancy. Tylor, no you can't get them ahead, starting your child off at a disadvantage, you don't know if you can do anything to give them a better start. Josh considered all options and considered the child and its mother, which is more mature than thinking that everything will come to those who work for it, which is not the case.
